    The root cause of the crash is a use-after-free error in the destroy_list   
    function due to incorrect order of operations in the loop.                  
                                                                                
    Walkthrough of Program State and Why the Crash Happens                      
                                                                                
     1 Initial Setup in main():                                                 
        • a points to a node with value 1, next pointing to b.                  
        • b points to value 2, next pointing to c.                              
        • c points to value 3, next is nullptr.                                 
        • The list: a -> b -> c -> nullptr                                      
     2 Entering destroy_list(a):                                                
        • head = a (the first node).                                            
        • The loop runs: for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; cur =           
          cur->next)                                                            
     3 First Iteration:                                                         
        • cur = a (valid pointer).                                              
        • delete cur; is called → a is deallocated.                             
        • Now, a is no longer a valid object.                                   
        • But cur is updated via cur = cur->next → cur = a->next = b.           
        • Even though a is deleted, the next pointer from a is still            
          accessible at this moment (since it's part of the data structure      
          before deallocation).                                                 
       ✅ So far, this may seem okay — a->next is still a valid pointer         
       because the next member is a Node* and wasn't overwritten.               
     4 Second Iteration:                                                        
        • cur = b (valid pointer).                                              
        • delete cur; → b is deallocated.                                       
        • Then cur = cur->next → cur = b->next = c.                             
     5 Third Iteration:                                                         
        • cur = c (valid).                                                      
        • delete cur; → c is deallocated.                                       
        • Then cur = cur->next → cur = c->next = nullptr.                       
     6 Loop Ends: cur is nullptr, so loop exits.                                
                                                                                
    So far, everything seems okay?                                              
                                                                                
    ✅ Wait — Why the "Use of deallocated memory" Error?                        
                                                                                
    The fatal issue is not in the listed destroy_list function, but in how the  
    cur->next is accessed after deletion.                                       
                                                                                
    Let’s re-examine the loop:                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; cur = cur->next) {                  
         delete cur;                                                            
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
     • The loop uses cur->next during the iteration, even after cur has been    
       deleted.                                                                 
                                                                                
    But cur->next is accessed in the loop condition only at the end of the      
    loop body via cur = cur->next.                                              
                                                                                
    So the real flaw is: cur is a pointer to a deleted object, yet we still     
    access cur->next after deletion.                                            
                                                                                
    But that access happens after delete cur — within the same iteration,       
    during the assignment:                                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     cur = cur->next                                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Which is after the delete cur call.                                         
                                                                                
    That means:                                                                 
                                                                                
     • cur points to a deleted object (a in first iteration),                   
     • Then we do cur = cur->next → but cur is no longer valid, so accessing    
       .next is undefined behavior, and may trigger a use-after-free error.     
                                                                                
    So even though a->next might still be a valid pointer in memory,            
    dereferencing cur (which points to a deleted object) to read next is the    
    problem.                                                                    
                                                                                
    This is exactly what the use-after-free error reports.                      
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    🔍 Why weren't cur or head visible in frame variable?                       
                                                                                
    Because debug was run at line 12, before the loop body starts. The cur and  
    head variables haven’t been initialized in the debugger's scope at that     
    point, so frame variable fails.                                             
                                                                                
    But print head also failed — likely because it was called on the wrong      
    line or debug info is missing — but we observed the program's behavior.     
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    ✅ Root Cause                                                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
     for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; cur = cur->next) {                  
         delete cur;  // Deletes the node, making cur invalid                   
     } // Then `cur` is updated via `cur = cur->next`, but cur is already       
     invalid!                                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
    👉 The cur->next is accessed after delete cur, meaning we read from a       
    deallocated object.                                                         
                                                                                
    This violates the strict aliasing and safety rules of delete. Even if the   
    next pointer was preserved, reading it from a deleted object is undefined   
    behavior.                                                                   
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    🔧 Fix: Use Temporary Pointer to Save next Before Deletion                  
                                                                                
    We must save the next pointer before deleting the current node.             
                                                                                
    ✅ Minimal Local Fix (Direct Fix to destroy_list)                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_list(Node *head) {                                     
         for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; ) {                             
             Node *next = cur->next;  // Save next *before* deletion            
             delete cur;                                                        
             cur = next;              // Move to next node                      
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This avoids accessing cur->next after deletion.                             
                                                                                
    ✅ Thorough Root-Cause Fix                                                  
                                                                                
    Also consider:                                                              
                                                                                
     • Never access fields of a deleted object.                                 
     • Encapsulate safe destruction logic in a helper function.                 
     • Avoid manual memory management when possible (use smart pointers).       
                                                                                
    But since this is a linked list example with raw pointers, the minimal fix  
    suffices.                                                                   
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    ##### Recommendation                                                        
                                                                                
    Replace the destroy_list function with:                                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_list(Node *head) {                                     
         for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; ) {                             
             Node *next = cur->next;                                            
             delete cur;                                                        
             cur = next;                                                        
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This fixes the use-after-free by ensuring that cur->next is accessed        
    before delete cur.                                                          
                                                                                
